maml:description.maml:para: Gets information about Data Factory.

The Get-AzureRmDataFactoryV2 cmdlet gets information about data factories in an Azure resource group. If you specify the name of a data factory, this cmdlet gets information about that data factory. If you do not specify a name, this cmdlet gets information about all of the data factories in an Azure resource group.

maml:Description.maml:para: Specifies the name of an Azure resource group. This cmdlet gets information about data factories that belong to the group that this parameter specifies.
Specifies the name of the data factory about which to get information.

command:example.dev:code: PS C:\>$DataFactory = Get-AzureRmDataFactoryV2 -ResourceGroupName "ADF" -Name "ContosoFactory"PS C:\> Get-AzureRmDataFactoryV2LinkedService -DataFactory $DataFactory | Format-Table -Property LinkedServiceName, DataFactoryName, ResourceGroupName

dev:remarks.maml:para: The first command uses the Get-AzureRmDataFactoryV2 cmdlet to get the data factory named ContosoFactory, and then stores it in the $DataFactory variable.

The second command gets information about the linked service for the data factory stored in $DataFactory, and then passes that information to the Format-Table cmdlet by using the pipeline operator. The Format-Table cmdlet formats the output as a dataset with the specified properties as dataset columns.

dev:remarks.maml:para: This command creates a pipeline named DPWikisample in the data factory named ADF. The command bases the pipeline on information in the DPWikisample.json file. This file includes information about activities such as Copy Activity and HDInsight Activity in the pipeline.

maml:description.maml:para: Creates a trigger in a data factory.

The Set-AzureRmDataFactoryV2Trigger cmdlet creates a trigger in a data factory. If you specify a name for a trigger that already exists, the cmdlet prompts for confirmation before replacing the trigger. If you specify the Force parameter, the cmdlet replaces the existing trigger without prompting for confirmation. Triggers are created in the 'Stopped' state, meaning that they will not immediately begin invoking pipelines that they reference.

command:example.dev:code:
PS C:\> Set-AzureRmDataFactoryV2Trigger -ResourceGroupName "ADF" -DataFactoryName "WikiADF" -Name "ScheduledTrigger" -DefinitionFile ".\scheduledTrigger.json"
TriggerName : ScheduledTrigger ResourceGroupName : ADF DataFactoryName : WikiADF Properties : Microsoft.Azure.Management.DataFactory.Models.ScheduleTrigger RuntimeState : Stopped

dev:remarks.maml:para: Create a new trigger called "ScheduledTrigger" in the data factory "WikiADF". The trigger is created in the 'Stopped' state, meaning that it will not be immediately started. A trigger can be started using the `Start-AzureRmDataFactoryV2Trigger` cmdlet.

maml:description.maml:para: Starts a trigger in a data factory.

The Start-AzureRmDataFactoryV2Trigger cmdlet starts a trigger in a data factory. If the trigger is in the 'Stopped' state, the cmdlet will start the trigger and it will eventually invoke pipelines based on its definition. If the trigger is already in the 'Started' state, this cmdlet will have no effect. If the Force parameter is specified, the cmdlet will not prompt before starting the trigger.

maml:description.maml:para: Stops a trigger in a data factory.

The Stop-AzureRmDataFactoryV2Trigger cmdlet stops a trigger in a data factory. If the trigger is in the 'Started' state, the cmdlet will stop the trigger and it will no longer invoke pipelines. If the trigger is already in the 'Stopped' state, this cmdlet will have no effect. If the Force parameter is specified, the cmdlet will not prompt before stopping the trigger.
